g.text: Cargo Shipping Company
UC101-Import ships from a text file
UC102-Search details of a ship
UC103-Have the positional message temporally organized
and associated with the ships
UC104-Make a summary of the ship's movements
UC105-List for all the ships the MMSI, the total number
of movements, Travelled Distance and Delta Distance
UC106-Get the top-N ships with the most kilometres travelled
and their average speed
UC107-Get pairs of ships with routes with close departure/arrival
coordinates and with different Travelled Distance
UC108-Develop the data model required to support all the functionality and
to fulfill the purpose of the system to develop
UC109-Draft an SQL script to test whether the database verifies
all the data integrity restrictions that are required
to fulfil the purpose of the system and the business constraints of the UoD
UC110-Define the naming conventions to apply
when defining identifiers or writing SQL or PL/SQL code
UC111-Create a SQL script to load the database
with a minimum set of data sufficient to carry out data
integrity verification and functional testing
UC201-Import ports from a text file
UC202-Find the closest port of a ship given its CallSign, on a certain DateTime
UC203-Review the relational data model in view of the new user stories
so it can support all the requirements to fulfil the purpose of the system being developed
UC204-Know the current situation of a specific container being used to transport my goods
UC205-Get the list of containers to be offloaded in the next port,
including container identifier, type, position, and load.
UC206-Get the list of containers to be loaded in the next port,
including container identifier, type, and load.
UC207-Know how many cargo manifests I have transported during
a given year and the average number of containers per manifest
UC208-Know the occupancy rate (percentage) of a given ship for
a given cargo manifest. Occupancy rate is the ratio between
total number of containers in the ship coming from a given manifest and the
total capacity of the ship, i.e., the maximum number of containers the ship can load.
UC209-Know the occupancy rate of a given ship at a given moment.
UC210-Know which ships will be available on Monday next week and their location
UC301-Import data from countries, ports, borders and seadists files from the database to build a freight network.
UC302-Colour the map using as few colours as possible
UC303-Know which places (cities or ports) are closest to all other places (closeness places).
UC304-Have access to audit trails for a given container of a given
cargo manifest, that is, I want to have access to a list of all
operations performed on a given container of a given manifest, in chronological order.
For each operation I want to know: the user/login that performed it,
the date and time the operation was performed, the type of operation (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE),
the container identifier and the cargo manifest identifier.
UC305-Know the route of a specific container I am leasing.
UC306-Know the occupancy rate of each warehouse and an estimate of
the containers leaving the warehouse during the next 30 days
UC307-Get a warning whenever I issue a cargo manifest destined for
a warehouse whose available capacity is insufficient to accommodate the new manifest.
UC308-Have a system that ensures that the number of containers
in a manifest does not exceed the ship's available capacity
UC309-Not allow a cargo manifest for a particular ship to be
registered in the system on a date when the ship is already occupied.
UC310-Have a map of the occupation of the existing resources in the port during a given month.
UC311-Provide a database access account, with login “crew”
and password “bd7wd5aF”, which gives access exclusively to the information
of the containers that are loaded on my ship. The information about
each container to be made available is: identifier, type, position and load
UC312-Know the current situation of a specific container being used to transport my goods
UC313-Fill a statically reserved matrix in memory with each container's ID in its respective place
UC314-Know the total number of free/occupied slots in the transport vehicle
UC315-Know if a container is there or not
UC316-Know the total number of occupied slots
UC317-Know what set of materials to use in a container, to operate at temperatures of 7°C
UC318-Know what set of materials to use in a container, to operate at temperatures of -5 °C
UC319-Know the thermal resistance, for each operating temperature,
of each container that must contain at least three different materials in its walls.
One for the outer wall, one for the intermediate material, and one for the inner wall.
UC320-Present in a summary document, the choice of materials considered for
the two types of containers considered, and their thermal resistances.
UC401-Know which ports are more critical (have greatercentrality) in this freight network.
UC402-Know the shortest path between two locals (city and/or port).
UC403-Know the most efficient circuit that starts from a source location and visits the greatest number
of other locations once, returning to the starting location and with the shortest total distance.
UC404-Know the number of days each ship has been idle since the beginning of the current year.
UC405-Know the average occupancy rate per manifest of a given ship during a given period.
UC406-Know which ship voyages - place and date of origin and destination - had an occupancy rate below a
certain threshold; by default, consider an occupancy rate threshold of 66%.
Only the trips already concluded are to be considered.
UC407-Generate, a week in advance, the loading and unloading map based on ships and trucks load manifests and
corresponding travel plans, to anticipate the level of sufficient and necessary resources (loading and unloading staff, warehouse staff, ...).
UC408-Develop a data model to build a Data Warehouse to analyse the volume of maritime traffic
between any two ports. The fact to be analysed is the traffic volume measured by the indicators “number
of containers”, “accumulated number of containers” and “target number of containers”.
These indicators refer to the number of containers that are in transit between two ports/locations
on the first day of each month. The dimensions to consider are Time, Port of origin and Port of destination.
The Time dimension has a hierarchy with the following levels: Year, Month. The location/Port
is subject to the following hierarchy: Continent, Country, Port. An estimate of the upper cardinality
of the dimension and fact tables must be indicated.
UC409-Fill a dynamically reserved array in memory with all the container's information in its respective place.
UC410-Know the amount of needed energy to keep the container at its required temperature.
UC411-Receive an alert when the current energy generation units are
not enough to provide energy to all refrigerated containers at once.
UC412-Know how much energy to supply, for each container, in a determined
trip, with an exterior temperature of 20 ºC, and a travel time of 2h30.
UC413-Know the total energy to be supplied to the set of containers in a
certain established trip, assuming that all the containers have the same behaviour.
UC414-Know how much energy to supply to the container cargo, in a voyage (or route),
depending on the position of the containers on the ship. Admitting that the interior
containers, or the sides not exposed directly to the "sun", maintain
the initial temperature, or of departure. However, the exposed sides may present temperature variations during the trip.
UC415-Know how many auxiliary power equipment are needed
for the voyage, knowing that each one supplies a maximum of 75 KW.
UC416-Submit a summary document, with the following items.
UC417-Want the technical team to search for at least three types
of ship/vessels that are better suited to the task (e.g., depending on the type of cargo), in which
the “control” bridge can assume three positions, one in the bow, one in the stern, and finally in the midship.
UC418-Want the determine the unladen center of mass for each vessel (if different) according
to its characteristics. For calculation purposes, consider known geometric figures.
UC419-Know where to position, for example, one hundred (100) containers on the
vessel, such that the center of mass remains at xx and yy, determined in the previous point.
UC420-Know for a specific vessel, how much did the vessel sink, assuming that each container has half a ton of mass.
